\begin_layout Plain Layout
\begin_inset Formula $\Question$
\end_inset

Prove the following for an 
\begin_inset Formula $m\times n$
\end_inset

 matrix 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
(i) If 
\begin_inset Formula $\v x\in\mathscr{N}\left(A\H A\right)$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $A\v x$
\end_inset

 is in both 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{R}(A)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{N}\left(A\H\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
(ii) 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathscr{N}\left(A\H A\right)=\mathscr{N}\left(A\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
(iii) 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $A\H A$
\end_inset

 have the same rank.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
(iv) If 
\begin_inset Formula $A$
\end_inset

 has linearly independent columns, then 
\begin_inset Formula $A\H A$
\end_inset

 is nonsingular.
\end_layout

\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Newline newline
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\Answer$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
(i) If 
\begin_inset Formula $\v x\in\mathscr{N}(A\H A)$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\v 0=(A\H A)\v x=A\H(A\v x)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $Ax\in\mathscr{N}(A\H)$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $A\v x\in\im(A)$
\end_inset

 by definition.
\begin_inset Formula $\qed$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
(ii) If 
\begin_inset Formula $\v x\in\mathscr{N}(A)$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $A\v x=\v 0$
\end_inset

.
 Then, 
\begin_inset Formula $A\H A\v x=A\H\v 0=\v 0$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $\v x\in\mathscr{N}(A\H A)$
\end_inset

.
 If 
\begin_inset Formula $\v x\in{\cal N}(A\H A)$
\end_inset

, then 
\begin_inset Formula $\n{A\v x}{}=\v x\H A\H A\v x=\v x\H\v 0=\v 0$
\end_inset

, so 
\begin_inset Formula $A\v x=\v 0$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\v x\in\mathscr{N}(A)$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Formula $\qed$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
(iii) 
\begin_inset Formula $n=\rank A+\dim(\mathscr{N}(A))$
\end_inset

 by rank-nullity, and 
\begin_inset Formula $n=\rank{A\H A}+\dim(\mathscr{N}(A\H A))$
\end_inset

.
 Then, by (ii), it follows that 
\begin_inset Formula $\rank A=\rank{A\H A}.$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula $\qed$
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Description
(iv) By (iii), we have that 
\begin_inset Formula $n=\rank A=\rank{A\H A}.$
\end_inset

 We know it is invertible by 
\begin_inset Formula $A\H A\in M_{n}$
\end_inset

.
\begin_inset Formula $\qed$
\end_inset


\end_layout

